Except from rare use cases you shouldn&#39;t call `setState` directly in your components render method and if you do so you need to be careful to chose the right condition to do so. 

Usually this is the case if your state depends on props provided to the component. The class based component lifecycle method is called `getDerivedStateFromProps`. You don&#39;t need that here.

It looks like you are trying to narrow down the result from your API endpoint. The transformation can be done in the fetch callback before calling `setPosts`:

    useEffect(() =&gt; {
        fetch(&quot;/index.json&quot;)
            .then(response =&gt; response.json())
            .then(function(data) {
                const allPosts = data.data.allContentfulPost.edges;
                const options = {
                    shouldSort: true,
                    threshold: 0.6,
                    location: 0,
                    distance: 100,
                    maxPatternLength: 32,
                    minMatchCharLength: 1,
                    keys: [&quot;node.title&quot;, &quot;node.meta&quot;],
                }
                const fuse = new Fuse(allPosts, options)
                const found = fuse.search(&quot;marketing&quot;)

                setPosts(found);
            })
    }, [])

