answers.body_markdown:
The problem arises from the fact that you can have one UserVote object per User/Blog/VoteType-combination.

Specifically, in the following lines

    self.post_votes.update(user=user, blog=self, vote_type=&#39;up&#39;)

    self.post_votes.update(user=user, blog=self, vote_type=&#39;down&#39;)

you are trying to update **all** vote objects that exist for the current blog to one of the vote_types. That means you potentially try to modify two UserVotes to have the exact same user, blog and vote_type, which causes an IntegrityError.



Thus, I would suggest only ever having one UserVote per User/Blog-combination instead of per User/Blog/VoteType-combination, i.e. change the unique_together to

    unique_together = (&#39;user&#39;, &#39;blog&#39;)

Then, you just have to change the type of the vote if the user has already voted on that blog. This prevents having an upvote and a downvote from the same user for the same blog at a time.

Also, you do not have to manually keep track of the total of upvotes and downvotes, you can get them straight from the count of UserVote objects. My suggested models.py looks something like this:


    from django.db import models


    class Blog(models.Model):
        title = models.CharField(max_length=100, blank=True, default=&#39;&#39;)
        description = models.TextField(max_length=1500)
        created = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)
        owner = models.ForeignKey(&#39;auth.User&#39;, related_name=&#39;blog&#39;, on_delete=models.CASCADE, null=True)
        image = models.FileField(blank=True, null=True)

        @property
        def votes(self):
            upvotes = UserVote.objects.filter(blog=self, vote_type=&#39;up&#39;).count()
            downvotes = UserVote.objects.filter(blog=self, vote_type=&#39;down&#39;).count()
            return upvotes - downvotes

        def upvote(self, user):
            vote, created = UserVote.objects.get_or_create(user=user, blog=self)
            if not created and vote.vote_type == &#39;up&#39;:
                return &#39;already_voted&#39;
            vote.vote_type = &#39;up&#39;
            vote.save()
            return &#39;ok&#39;

        def downvote(self, user):
            vote, created = UserVote.objects.get_or_create(user=user, blog=self)
            if not created and vote.vote_type == &#39;down&#39;:
                return &#39;already_voted&#39;
            vote.vote_type = &#39;down&#39;
            vote.save()
            return &#39;ok&#39;


    class UserVote(models.Model):
        user = models.ForeignKey(&#39;auth.User&#39;, related_name=&#39;user_votes&#39;, on_delete=models.CASCADE)
        blog = models.ForeignKey(Blog, related_name=&#39;post_votes&#39;, on_delete=models.CASCADE)
        vote_type = models.CharField(max_length=10)

        class Meta:
            unique_together = (&#39;user&#39;, &#39;blog&#39;)

I&#39;m sure there is a much more clever way to get the total of upvotes and downvotes using [aggregations](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/topics/db/aggregation/), this is just a quick working example.

